Feature 3: Delete Your Account
Users should be able to delete their own account. Once deleted, the user should no longer be able to log in, and their account information should be removed or no longer accessible.

Test account:testuser1

Acceptance Criteria:
User’s account  is deleted
All user comments  are  deleted 
All leaderboard  scores  are  deleted
Friendship removed from all  users they were friends  with
All metadata  associated  with user  is erased.

Initial condition:
Account exists.
Account may have sample comments, challenges, or friend relationships.
Acceptance Criteria
A logged-in user can access the account deletion option.
The user is asked to confirm before deletion.
After deletion, the account can no longer be used to log in.
Deleted user data should no longer appear in places where active user accounts are shown.
The app should redirect the user after account deletion.


Feature 3  test  1: Delete Account Successfully

Procedure:
Log in as testuser1.
Navigate to the profile or account settings page.
Select the delete account option.
Confirm account deletion.

Expected result:
The account is deleted.
 The user is logged out or redirected away from the profile page.
 The account is removed from the users table
All other data associated with user is gone

Actual result: Works as expected.

Feature  3 Test 2: Attempt Login After Account Deletion

Procedure:
Delete the testuser1 account.
Return to the login page.
Attempt to log in using testuser@example.com and Password123.

Expected result:
Login fails.
The app displays an error message such as invalid credentials or account not found.

Actual result:Our login page is the same field for registering a  new  account so it just makes a new account.

Feature  3  Test 3: Deleted Account Is Not Publicly Accessible

Procedure:
Delete the testuser1 account.
Log in as another user.
Attempt to navigate to /profile/testuser1.

Expected result:
The deleted user’s profile is not displayed.
The app shows an error, redirects, or indicates that the user does not exist.

Actual result: Error message because bad pathways just throw error codes.  Maybe  add something a little more polished?
